] (1997\u20131999)\n* [[FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup]] champion ([[1991\u201392 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup|1992]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Greek Basket League|Greek League]] champion (1998, 1999)\n* [[Greek Basket League Finals MVP|Greek League Finals MVP]] (1998)\n* 3\u00d7 [[Yugoslav First Federal Basketball League|Yugoslav League]] champion ([[1987\u201388 Yugoslav First Basketball League|1988]]\u2013[[1989\u201390 Yugoslav First Basketball League|1990]])\n* [[Yugoslavian Basketball Cup|Yugoslav Cup]] winner (1990)\n* 2\u00d7 [[HT Premijer liga|Croatian League]] champion (2002, 2003)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107 Cup|Croatian Cup]] winner (2000, 2002)\n* [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107 Cup|Croatian Cup]] MVP (2000)\n* [[Lega Basket All Star Game|Italian All-Star Game]] MVP (1991)\n* [[NBA All-Rookie Second Team]] ({{nbay|1993|end}})\n* [[FIBA's 50 Greatest Players]] (1991)\n* [[50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors]] (2008)\n| stats_league    = NBA\n| stat1label      = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value      = 3,733 (16.7 ppg)\n| stat2label      = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value      = 1,883 (8.4 rpg)\n| stat3label      = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value      = 356 (1.6 apg)\n| HOF_player      = dino-radja\n| bbr             = radjadi01\n| medal_templates = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| {{bk|YUG}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1988 Seoul]] | }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[EuroBasket 1987|1987 Greece]] | }}\n{{MedalGold| [[EuroBasket 1989|1989 Yugoslavia]] | }}\n{{MedalGold| [[EuroBasket 1991|1991 Italy]] | }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Under-19 World Cup|U19 World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1987 FIBA Under-19 World Championship|1987 Italy]]|[[Yugoslavia men's national under-19 basketball team|Under-19]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|European U-18 Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1986 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1986 Austria]]|[[Yugoslavia men's national under-18 basketball team|Under-18]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| {{bk|CRO}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1992 Barcelona]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[1994 FIBA World Championship|1994 Canada]] | }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[EuroBasket 1993|1993 Germany]] | }}\n{{MedalBronze| [[EuroBasket 1995|1995 Greece]] | }}\n}}\n'''Dino Ra\u0111a''' ([[Anglicized]]: '''Dino Radja''', {{IPA-sh|\u02ccd\u01d0\u02d0no \u02c8r\u00e2d\u035c\u0291a|hr}}; born 24 April 1967) is a Croatian former professional [[basketball]] player. He was a member of the [[KK Split|Jugoplastika]] team of the late 1980s and early 1990s, which he helped to win two [[FIBA European Champions Cup]] championships ([[1989 FIBA European Champions Cup Final Four|1989]] and [[1990 FIBA European Champions Cup Final Four|1990]]). He spent three and a half seasons with the [[Boston Celtics]], being one of the European pioneers in the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]. Ra\u0111a was named one of [[FIBA's 50 Greatest Players]] in 1991, and one of the [[50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors]] in 2008. He was inducted into the [[List of players in the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|Basketball Hall of Fame]], as a member of the 2018 class.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Split===\nRa\u0111a began his basketball life in his native town, as a junior at [[KK Dalvin]]. He moved to [[KK Split]], which at the time went under the name of its longtime naming-rights sponsor Jugoplastika. At KK Split, Ra\u0111a starred alongside [[Toni Kuko\u010d]], while both were teenagers. The duo led the team to dominance of the [[FIBA European Champions Cup]], with repeat championship seasons in ([[1989 FIBA European Champions Cup Final Four|1989]] and [[1990 FIBA European Champions Cup Final Four|1990]]).\n\n====1989\u201390 season: Defection to NBA and court-ordered return to Yugoslavia====\nIn late June 1989, the 22-year-old [[center (basketball)|center]] got [[1989 NBA draft|drafted]] by the [[Boston Celtics]] in the second round as the 40th pick. Right away, he publicly expressed willingness to go to [[Boston]] immediately \"if the financial offer is good\",<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1989-06-29/sports/sp-3793_1_jugoplastika-partizan-belgrade-yugoslav-national-team Coach Denies Yugoslav Will Join Celtics : But Lakers' Pick Will Be Permitted to Play in NBA];''Los Angeles Times'', 29 June 1989</ref> and thus join fellow Yugoslavs [[Vlade Divac]], [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]], and [[\u017darko Paspalj]], who were also on their way to the [[NBA]] that summer. However, led by the club's general manager Josip Bili\u0107, Jugoplastika was adamant Ra\u0111a would not be released since they had him under contract until 1992. The entire case quickly turned into a months-long saga that played out in the Yugoslav media. The club's [[head coach]], [[Bo\u017eidar Maljkovi\u0107]], even publicly called on the Yugoslav Basketball Association (KSJ) to adopt safeguard policies, preventing players younger than age 26 from transferring to NBA teams.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1989-06-30/sports/sp-3091_1_dino-radja-yugoslav-portland-trail-blazers Calling for safeguards against NBA raids on its players, a...];''Los Angeles Times'', 30 June 1989</ref> After weeks of wrangling over his status, Ra\u0111a tried to force Jugoplastika's hand by physically going over to the U.S. in early August 1989 and unilaterally signing a one-year contract with the Celtics,<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1989-08-02/sports/sp-704_1_boston-celtics Boston Celtics Sign Dino Radja];''Los Angeles Times'', 2 August 1989</ref> reportedly worth in the neighborhood of $500,000. He furthermore began practicing with the team at their [[Brandeis University]] training facilities.<ref>[http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1989-08-03/sports/8908032084_1_radja-celtics-unsupportive Celts Sign Yugoslav];''Orlando Sentinel'', 3 August 1989</ref> However, seeing the situation as a clear case of contract poaching by Boston and its general manager [[Jan Volk]] (who claimed Ra\u0111a's contract with Jugoplastika was [[amateur sports|amateur]] and thus non-binding), the Split club would not give up the legal fight, taking the case to the [[United States district court]] for the [[United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts|District of Massachusetts]] and seeking an [[injunction]] to prevent Ra\u0111a from playing for the Celtics on the grounds that he had a valid and legally binding contract with them. Following a hearing on 26 September 1989, Judge [[Douglas P. Woodlock|Douglas Woodlock]] ruled in their favor two days later thus preventing Ra\u0111a from playing for the Celtics.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1989-09-26/sports/sp-374_1_boston-celtics U.S. Court Bars Yugoslav Star From Joining Celtics];''Los Angeles Times'', 26 September 1989</ref> Since Ra\u0111a was physically already in Boston, bringing him back to Yugoslavia required some kind of an agreement. By mid-November 1989, Jugoplastika and the Celtics agreed to terms under which the player went back to complete the 1989\u201390 season in Split before having the rights to his services transferred to the Celtics effective 1 June 1990.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=TnkuSogCVyIC&pg=PA664&lpg=PA664&dq=Radja+Boston+Celtics+contract&source=bl&ots=Mvb9RhK7i6&sig=6xqufIFsHNV0cJtw_zrXfAiD0L4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JtdNUarNLYKS2QX-1oH4AQ&ved=0CF8Q6AEwCTgK#v=onepage&q=Radja%20Boston%20Celtics%20contract&f=false International Sports Law and Business, volume 1];Aaron N. Wise, Bruce S. Meyer, 1997, p.664</ref> The deal centered around the Celtics paying an undisclosed sum of money to Jugoplastika, which in turn agreed to let Ra\u0111a go two years short of his contract's completion.<ref>[http://www.deseretnews.com/article/111792/RADJA-NOW-FREE-TO-PLAY-FOR-CELTICS.html?pg=all RADJA NOW FREE TO PLAY FOR CELTICS];''Desert News'', 11 July 1990</ref>\n[[File:Toni Kuko\u010d-Dino Ra\u0111a-Jugoplastika.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Ra\u0111a celebrates winning Split's second consecutive continental title with teammate [[Toni Kuko\u010d]], after beating [[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet|FC Barcelona]] at the [[1989\u201390 FIBA European Champions Cup|FIBA European Champions Cup]] [[1990 FIBA European Champions Cup Final Four|Final Four]] final game in [[Zaragoza]] on 19 April 1990.]]\nRa\u0111a was thus back in Split for the 1989\u201390 season. That same season, Jugoplastika again won the [[Yugoslav Basketball League|Yugoslav League]], its third consecutive national domestic league title, as well as its second straight [[FIBA European Champions Cup]].\n\nDespite the team's success, as previously agreed, Ra\u0111a would not stay in Split past June 1990 thus relinquishing the chance to go for the historic FIBA European Champions Cup [[three-peat]] (which the club, led by Kuko\u010d, achieved the following year), but he would not go to Boston either.\n\n===Rome===\nIn August 1990, instead of going to the [[NBA]] as previously agreed, Ra\u0111a went to Italy, signing with the wealthy [[Pallacanestro Virtus Roma|Virtus Roma]] despite claiming all along that he had wanted to join the Celtics.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1990-03-19/sports/sp-504_1_boston-celtics Radja Says Club Is Ready to Let Him Be a Celtic];''Los Angeles Times'', 19 March 1990</ref> He changed his mind once Virtus, an ambitious and financially stable club bankrolled by the [[:it:Ferruzzi|Gruppo Ferruzzi]] food company and sponsored by the daily broadsheet ''[[Il Messaggero]]'', made him an offer reportedly in the [[US$]]15\u201318 million range for a 5-year contract.<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite magazine | url = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1136568/index.htm | author = [[Jack McCallum]] | title = Close But No Cigar: The sagging Celts were spurned by Brian Shaw and by Dino Radja | magazine = [[Sports Illustrated]] | date = 13 August 1990 | accessdate = 23 February 2012}}</ref> Italian and Yugoslav newspapers reported that Ra\u0111a's annual salary at the time, [[Italian lira|L]]3.6 billion, at Virtus was higher than soccer superstars [[Diego Maradona]]'s and [[Roberto Baggio]]'s annual compensations at [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] and [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], respectively.<ref name=\"Zlatnimomci\">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yklhi8h1Cu4&t=1322|first1=Vladimir|last1=Paji\u0107|first2=Milo\u0161|last2=\u0160akan|title=Zlatni momci (episode 3): Tim snova u luna parku|agency=[[Radio Television of Serbia]]|date=28 August 2019|accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> The Boston Celtics did not insist on Ra\u0111a honouring his commitment to them, instead letting the twenty-three-year-old go to Virtus in return for an undisclosed amount,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1990/08/03/sports/sports-people-pro-basketball-radja-to-roma-team-for-two-seasons.html Radja to Roma Team For Two Seasons];''The New York Times'', 3 August 1990</ref> but retaining his NBA rights. Reportedly, part of the reason Boston did not put up much of a fight when the player suddenly decided to sign with Virtus was the July 1990 court decision against them following the motion by Ra\u0111a's American [[sports agent|agent]], Marc Fleisher, after the Virtus offer came in. Taking advantage of an administrative loophole,<ref>{{cite news|last=Arace|first=Michael|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-08-23/sports/sp-1950_1_reggie-lewis|title=Reggie Lewis Signed Up by Celtics for 5 Years|agency=''[[Los Angeles Times]]''|date=23 August 1990|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> Fleisher claimed that Ra\u0111a's contract with the Celtics violated a provision of the agreement between the league and the NBA players that said, among other things, that one-year contracts could not be extended. A special officer of the court had heard the case and ruled in Ra\u0111a's favour, against the Celtics.<ref name=\"SI\"/>\n\nSimultaneous to the legal battle his agent was waging over the future of his club career, Ra\u0111a had been spending the summer of 1990 with the [[Yugoslavia national basketball team|Yugoslav national team]] in a four-month training camp for the [[1990 FIBA World Championship]] that included an appearance at the [[1990 Goodwill Games]] in [[Seattle]] where the 23-year-old suffered a leg fracture in the final game against the [[United States men's national basketball team|U.S. national team]], ruling him out of the World Championship that started a week later. Yugoslavia head coach [[Du\u0161an Ivkovi\u0107]] later revealed that injured Ra\u0111a and the center's agent Marc Fleisher asked him not to publicly disclose the player's injury before the deal with Virtus is signed, which Ivkovi\u0107 consented to.<ref name=\"Zlatnimomci\"/>\n\nSome observers saw Virtus' sudden and lucrative contract offer to Ra\u0111a as their retribution to the Celtics for going to court a few months earlier over enforcing Virtus' point guard [[Brian Shaw]]'s NBA contract and winning the case even after the player who had spent the previous 1989-90 season with Virtus tried to remain in Rome.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com.au/boston/nba/columns/story?columnist=may_peter&id=5685362|first=Peter|last=May|title=Erden brings new dimension to C's|newspaper=[[ESPN.com]]|date=14 October 2010|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, commenting on his summer 1990 decision to stay in Europe, even after only a year prior seeming desperately intent on playing in the NBA, Ra\u0111a said: {{cquote|''I was playing well. I was making a great salary in Europe. The thing about playing in the NBA was that there were so many unknowns. The NBA was more physical because the players were bigger and stronger than in Europe. I also would have had to get used to an entirely different culture''.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=eMPHqkXjbM0C&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=Radja+Vrankovic+Boston+Celtics&source=bl&ots=_L--OZung3&sig=6zebbkVqSW2dk4GHtGaH-6grLUM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FcVNUZ2SEoLi4AO67oHoDA&ved=0CCwQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=Radja%20Vrankovic%20Boston%20Celtics&f=false Boston Celtics: Where Have You Gone?];Mike Carey, Michael D. McClellan 2005, p.52</ref>}}\n\n====1990-91 season====\nRa\u0111a averaged 17.9 points in the [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italian League]]<ref name=\"web.legabasket.it\">[http://web.legabasket.it/player/?id=RAD-DIN-67 Dino Radja MEDIE STAGIONE {{in lang|it}}.]</ref> in his first season with [[Pallacanestro Virtus Roma|Il Messaggero]] (Virtus Roma enjoyed sponsorship from that [[Il Messaggero|popular Roman newspaper]] at the time). European sports journalists voted him the second best European player that season, behind only his former teammate and friend Kuko\u010d.\n\nHe improved his scoring average each of the next two seasons with the Roman club, averaging 20.3 and 21.7 points in the Italian League,<ref name=\"web.legabasket.it\"/> respectively.\n\nIn 1992, he [[1991\u201392 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup|led]] Virtus to a [[European professional club basketball system|European 3rd-tier level]] [[FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup]] title.\n\n===Boston Celtics===\nRa\u0111a finally joined the Celtics in the summer of 1993, signing a three-year contract on 9 July,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1993/07/10/sports/sports-people-basketball-celtics-complete-radja-deal.html Celtics Complete Radja Deal];''The New York Times'', 10 July 1993</ref> four years after initial interest from both parties and the voided contract in 1989. Some two and a half weeks later, the team went through a shocking incident when the Celtics' leading scorer, [[small forward]] [[Reggie Lewis]], died on the basketball court at the team's [[Brandeis University]] practice facility after suffering [[sudden cardiac death]] from a heart defect.\n\nPlaying alongside [[Dee Brown (basketball, born 1968)|Dee Brown]], 40-year-old veteran [[Robert Parish]], and [[Rick Fox]], twenty-six-year-old Ra\u0111a averaged 15.1 points and 7.2 rebounds in his [[1993\u201394 Boston Celtics season|debut season]] during which he made $1.5 million in salary.<ref>[http://articles.courant.com/1993-11-02/sports/0000002573_1_dino-radja-celtics-coach-chris-ford-dave-gavitt Celtics' Radja Proving He Belongs];''Hartford Courant'', 2 November 1993</ref> With a 32\u201350 regular season record, the Celtics missed the NBA playoffs, finishing 10th overall in the eastern conference. At the end of the season, Ra\u0111a was voted to the [[NBA All-Rookie Team|NBA All-Rookie Second Team]], along with Kuko\u010d, who had just completed his rookie campaign with the [[Chicago Bulls]].\n\nIn early November 1994, at the start of [[1994\u201395 Boston Celtics season|his second season]] with the Celtics, Ra\u0111a was looking for a contract extension on his existing three-year deal, which was expiring in the summer of 1996. With his agent Mark Fleisher engaged in long negotiations<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924201131/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8303175.html Radja looks like lost cause With extension unlikely, escape looms];''The Boston Globe'', 8 November 1994</ref> with the Celtics brass led by GM Jan Volk, the deal was reached to add three more years to Ra\u0111a's existing contract beginning with the 1996\u201397 season.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1290&dat=19941109&id=B1JUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=t40DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3311,4386566 Celtics, Radja agree contract extension];''Boca Raton News'', 9 November 1994</ref>\n\nThe 1996\u201397 season, Ra\u0111a's fourth in Boston, was marked by a left knee injury that forced him to miss 57 regular season games. In January 1997, he underwent [[arthroscopic surgery]] on his knee. The Celtics finished the season dead-last in their division, with a 15\u201367 record, the worst in the eastern conference, forcing a coaching change at the end of the season, with [[Rick Pitino]] replacing [[M. L. Carr]].\n\nIn June 1997, a trade that was to send thirty-year-old Ra\u0111a to the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] (in exchange for [[Clarence Weatherspoon]] and [[Michael Cage]]) fell through when Ra\u0111a failed his 24 June 1997 physical with the 76ers. Apparently, the 76ers staffers that examined Ra\u0111a determined he had no [[cartilage]] in his left knee, estimating that \"because his left knee is bone-on-bone, he can play games, but he can't practice afterwards, because his knee will swell\" and that \"he can't play four games in six days\".<ref>[http://articles.philly.com/1997-06-27/sports/25525198_1_sixers-dino-radja-nets-trade Boston Drops Radja Challenge];''The Inquirer'', 27 June 1997</ref> The Celtics initially challenged the 76ers' decision to void the trade, but quickly dropped their arbitration request. Ra\u0111a had three more years left on his guaranteed contract and, according to the NBA regulations, if he was to fail another team's physical, the Celtics would have to pay his entire remaining salary. Unconvinced about Ra\u0111a's physical condition, the Celtics gave up on trying to trade him, instead agreeing a buyout of the three years that remained on his contract. Following the buyout, the Celtics waived Ra\u0111a on 16 July 1997.\n\nIn 2005, Ra\u0111a talked about his exit from Boston: {{cquote|''I went to Pitino and asked him if I fit into his plans. With a new coach, I obviously wanted to know what he thought of my game. I loved playing for Boston and just wanted to find out if there was any possibility I might be traded, because I had heard some rumours. Pitino looked me right in the eyes and said, \"Dino, don't worry. You're going to be a big part of our offense. When we run a set play, the ball is going to go through you.' I left the meeting feeling great. Five days later, I found out I was being traded to Philadelphia. I can't tell you how much I felt betrayed. Either Pitino lied or something changed in a matter of a few days.\"<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=eMPHqkXjbM0C&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=Radja+Vrankovic+Boston+Celtics&source=bl&ots=_L--OZung3&sig=6zebbkVqSW2dk4GHtGaH-6grLUM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FcVNUZ2SEoLi4AO67oHoDA&ved=0CCwQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=Radja%20Vrankovic%20Boston%20Celtics&f=false Boston Celtics: Where Have You Gone?];Mike Carey, Michael D. McClellan 2005, p.54</ref>}}\n\nOver the course of his four seasons with the Celtics, Ra\u0111a averaged 16.7 points and 8.4 rebounds per game in the regular season. In the NBA playoffs, where he only made a single appearance with four games played, he averaged 15.0 points and 7.0 rebounds per game.\n\n===Return to Europe: Panathinaikos===\nIn the wake of his failed physical in Philadelphia and Rick Pitino's unwillingness to keep him on the Celtics' roster, Ra\u0111a returned to Europe in July 1997, joining [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]], a rich and ambitious club bankrolled by the Giannakopoulos brothers ([[Pavlos Giannakopoulos|Pavlos]] and [[Thanasis Giannakopoulos|Thanasis]]) who made their money in the pharmaceutical industry.\n\nFor Panathinaikos' owners, finishing the previous 1996\u201397 season without any trophies (having previously, in the 1995\u201396 season, won both the [[FIBA European League]] and the [[Greek Basketball Cup|Greek Cup]]) was deemed unacceptable, bringing about big changes to the team. The team's head coach [[Bo\u017eidar Maljkovi\u0107]] (Ra\u0111a's mentor from his Split days) had already been released during the previous failed season, while his interim replacement, Michalis Kokalis, was let go in the summer of 1997 to make way for new head coach [[Slobodan Suboti\u0107]]. Also coming in alongside Ra\u0111a and coach Suboti\u0107, was 36-year-old NBA veteran [[Byron Scott (basketball)|Byron Scott]] from the [[LA Lakers]].\n\nRa\u0111a spent two years in Athens, winning two [[Greek Basket League|Greek League]] championships, but in 1999, he returned to his native Croatia, to play for [[KK Zadar|Zadar]]. He left Panathinaikos partly because of an encounter with [[Pavlos Giannakopoulos|the club president]]'s son, [[Dimitrios Giannakopoulos]], in the locker room after a game. The president's son, [[Dimitrios Giannakopoulos|Dimitrios]], allegedly cursed at the team's head coach Suboti\u0107, but at that time, Ra\u0111a did not know that the person he was arguing with was the son of the club's president.<ref>http://www.blog.hr/print/id/1623177546/dezbjego-show-slobodan-subotic.html {{in lang|hr}}</ref> He left the club at the end of the season, after winning the Greek League finals against [[Olympiacos B.C.|Olympiacos]].\n\nIn 2000, he returned to Greece, joining Panathinaikos' long-time rivals, [[Olympiacos B.C.|Olympiacos]], in an unsuccessful attempt to regain the Greek League championship. With Olympiacos, on 16 October 2000, he scored his first points in the [[EuroLeague]] competition, under its new format in which it was run by [[Euroleague Basketball]], in a match against [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]].<ref>http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/5teeg5mf8yhh44wj/euroleague-s-500-000th-point-scored-on-friday</ref>\n\nHe returned, once again, to Croatia, joining [[KK Cibona|Cibona]] for the 2001\u201302 season. Ra\u0111a finished his career in 2003, by winning the [[A1 Liga|Croatian League]] championship with his first team, [[KK Split|Split CO]].\n\n==National team career==\nRa\u0111a was on the senior men's [[Yugoslavian national basketball team|Yugoslavian national team]] that won the silver medal in the [[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1988 Summer Olympic Games]] in [[Seoul]]. He was also a part of the golden Yugoslavian teams at the [[1987 FIBA Under-19 World Championship]] in [[Bormio]], Italy, [[EuroBasket 1989]] in [[Zagreb]] and the [[EuroBasket 1991]] in Rome.\n\nFollowing Croatia's independence, Ra\u0111a became an important player of the senior men's [[Croatian national basketball team]], most notably at the [[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1992 Summer Olympic Games]] in [[Barcelona]], where Croatia won the silver medal. Ra\u0111a was also on the Croatian teams that won the bronze at the [[EuroBasket 1993]] in Germany, [[1994 FIBA World Championship]] in [[Toronto]], and the [[EuroBasket 1995]] in [[Athens]]. With 1,764 points scored, he was the all-time top scorer for the Croatian national team until 2018, when he was surpassed by [[Bojan Bogdanovi\u0107]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/kapetan-zabio-1471-kos-ukic-postao-treci-najbolji-strijelac-hrvatske-svih-vremena--znate-li-tko-su-prva-dvojica-/1217742/|title=Uki\u0107 tre\u0107i najbolji strijelac Hrvatske svih vremena, znate li tko su prva dvojica?|work=[[Jutarnji list]]|date=4 September 2014|language=Croatian|accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.index.hr/sport/clanak/bogdanovic-novi-hrvatski-rekorder-u-poenima-prestigao-radju/2023912.aspx|title=Bogdanovi\u0107 novi hrvatski rekorder u poenima: Prestigao Ra\u0111u|date=14 September 2018|work=[[Index.hr]]|language=hr|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==NBA career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===Regular season===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1993}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1993\u201394 Boston Celtics season|Boston]]\n| '''80''' || 47 || 28.8 || '''.521''' || .000 || .751 || 7.2 || 1.4 || .9 || .8 || 15.1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1994}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1994\u201395 Boston Celtics season|Boston]]\n| 66 || 48 || 32.5 || .490 || .000 || '''.759''' || 8.7 || 1.7 || .9 || 1.3 || 17.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1995}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1995\u201396 Boston Celtics season|Boston]]\n| 53 || '''52''' || '''37.4''' || .500 || {{sort|-|\u2014}} || .695 || '''9.8''' || 1.6 