e|Italian All-Star Game]] MVP (1991)\n* [[NBA All-Rookie Second Team]] ({{nbay|1993|end}})\n* [[FIBA's 50 Greatest Players]] (1991)\n* [[50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors]] (2008)\n| stats_league    = NBA\n| stat1label      = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value      = 3,733 (16.7 ppg)\n| stat2label      = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value      = 1,883 (8.4 rpg)\n| stat3label      = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value      = 356 (1.6 apg)\n| HOF_player      = dino-radja\n| bbr             = radjadi01\n| medal_templates = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| {{bk|YUG}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1988 Seoul]] | }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[EuroBasket 1987|1987 Greece]] | }}\n{{MedalGold| [[EuroBasket 1989|1989 Yugoslavia]] | }}\n{{MedalGold| [[EuroBasket 1991|1991 Italy]] | }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Under-19 World Cup|U19 World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1987 FIBA Under-19 World Championship|1987 Italy]]|[[Yugoslavia men's national under-19 basketball team|Under-19]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|European U-18 Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1986 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1986 Austria]]|[[Yugoslavia men's national under-18 basketball team|Under-18]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| {{bk|CRO}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1992 Barcelona]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[1994 FIBA World Championship|1994 Canada]] | }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[EuroBasket 1993|1993 Germany]] | }}\n{{MedalBronze| [[EuroBasket 1995|1995 Greece]] | }}\n}}\n'''Dino Ra\u0111a''' ([[Anglicized]]: '''Dino Radja''', {{IPA-sh|\u02ccd\u01d0\u02d0no \u02c8r\u00e2d\u035c\u0291a|hr}}; born 24 April 1967) is a Croatian former professional [[basketball]] player. He was a member of the [[KK Split|Jugoplastika]] team of the late 1980s and early 1990s, which he helped to win two [[FIBA European Champions Cup]] championships ([[1989 FIBA European Champions Cup Final Four|1989]] and [[1990 FIBA European Champions Cup Final Four|1990]]). He spent three and a half seasons with the [[Boston Celtics]], being one of the European pioneers in the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]. Ra\u0111a was named one of [[FIBA's 50 Greatest Players]] in 1991, and one of the [[50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors]] in 2008. He was inducted into the [[List of players in the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|Basketball Hall of Fame]], as a member of the 2018 class.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Split===\nRa\u0111a began his basketball life in his native town, as a junior at [[KK Dalvin]]. He moved to [[KK Split]], which at the time went under the name of its longtime naming-rights sponsor Jugoplastika. At KK Split, Ra\u0111a starred alongside [[Toni Kuko\u010d]], while both were teenagers. The duo led the team to dominance of the [[FIBA European Champions Cup]], with repeat championship seasons in ([[1989 FIBA European Champions Cup Final Four|1989]] and [[1990 FIBA European Champions Cup Final Four|1990]]).\n\n====1989\u201390 season: Defection to NBA and court-ordered return to Yugoslavia====\nIn late June 1989, the 22-year-old [[center (basketball)|center]] got [[1989 NBA draft|drafted]] by the [[Boston Celtics]] in the second round as the 40th pick. Right away, he publicly expressed willingness to go to [[Boston]] immediately \"if the financial offer is good\",<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1989-06-29/sports/sp-3793_1_jugoplastika-partizan-belgrade-yugoslav-national-team Coach Denies Yugoslav Will Join Celtics : But Lakers' Pick Will Be Permitted to Play in NBA];''Los Angeles Times'', 29 June 1989</ref> and thus join fellow Yugoslavs [[Vlade Divac]], [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]], and [[\u017darko Paspalj]], who were also on their way to the [[NBA]] that summer. However, led by the club's general manager Josip Bili\u0107, Jugoplastika was adamant Ra\u0111a would not be released since they had him under contract until 1992. The entire case quickly turned into a months-long saga that played out in the Yugoslav media. The club's [[head coach]], [[Bo\u017eidar Maljkovi\u0107]], even publicly called on the Yugoslav Basketball Association (KSJ) to adopt safeguard policies, preventing players younger than age 26 from transferring to NBA teams.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1989-06-30/sports/sp-3091_1_dino-radja-yugoslav-portland-trail-blazers Calling for safeguards against NBA raids on its players, a...];''Los Angeles Times'', 30 June 1989</ref> After weeks of wrangling over his status, Ra\u0111a tried to force Jugoplastika's hand by physically going over to the U.S. in early August 1989 and unilaterally signing a one-year contract with the Celtics,<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1989-08-02/sports/sp-704_1_boston-celtics Boston Celtics Sign Dino Radja];''Los Angeles Times'', 2 August 1989</ref> reportedly worth in the neighborhood of $500,000. He furthermore began practicing with the team at their [[Brandeis University]] training facilities.<ref>[http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1989-08-03/sports/8908032084_1_radja-celtics-unsupportive Celts Sign Yugoslav];''Orlando Sentinel'', 3 August 1989</ref> However, seeing the situation as a clear case of contract poaching by Boston and its general manager [[Jan Volk]] (who claimed Ra\u0111a's contract with Jugoplastika was [[amateur sports|amateur]] and thus non-binding), the Split club would not give up the legal fight, taking the case to the [[United States district court]] for the [[United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts|District of Massachusetts]] and seeking an [[injunction]] to prevent Ra\u0111a from playing for the Celtics on the grounds that he had a valid and legally binding contract with them. Following a hearing on 26 September 1989, Judge [[Douglas P. Woodlock|Douglas Woodlock]] ruled in their favor two days later thus preventing Ra\u0111a from playing for the Celtics.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1989-09-26/sports/sp-374_1_boston-celtics U.S. Court Bars Yugoslav Star From Joining Celtics];''Los Angeles Times'', 26 September 1989</ref> Since Ra\u0111a was physically already in Boston, bringing him back to Yugoslavia required some kind of an agreement. By mid-November 1989, Jugoplastika and the Celtics agreed to terms under which the player went back to complete the 1989\u201390 season in Split before having the rights to his services transferred to the Celtics effective 1 June 1990.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=TnkuSogCVyIC&pg=PA664&lpg=PA664&dq=Radja+Boston+Celtics+contract&source=bl&ots=Mvb9RhK7i6&sig=6xqufIFsHNV0cJtw_zrXfAiD0L4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JtdNUarNLYKS2QX-1oH4AQ&ved=0CF8Q6AEwCTgK#v=onepage&q=Radja%20Boston%20Celtics%20contract&f=false International Sports Law and Business, volume 1];Aaron N. Wise, Bruce S. Meyer, 1997, p.664</ref> The deal centered around the Celtics paying an undisclosed sum of money to Jugoplastika, which in turn agreed to let Ra\u0111a go two years short of his contract's completion.<ref>[http://www.deseretnews.com/article/111792/RADJA-NOW-FREE-TO-PLAY-FOR-CELTICS.html?pg=all RADJA NOW FREE TO PLAY FOR CELTICS];''Desert News'', 11 July 1990</ref>\n[[File:Toni Kuko\u010d-Dino Ra\u0111a-Jugoplastika.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Ra\u0111a celebrates winning Split's second consecutive continental title with teammate [[Toni Kuko\u010d]], after beating [[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet|FC Barcelona]] at the [[1989\u201390 FIBA European Champions Cup|FIBA European Champions Cup]] [[1990 FIBA European Champions Cup Final Four|Final Four]] final game in [[Zaragoza]] on 19 April 1990.]]\nRa\u0111a was thus back in Split for the 1989\u201390 season. That same season, Jugoplastika again won the [[Yugoslav Basketball League|Yugoslav League]], its third consecutive national domestic league title, as well as its second straight [[FIBA European Champions Cup]].\n\nDespite the team's success, as previously agreed, Ra\u0111a would not stay in Split past June 1990 thus relinquishing the chance to go for the historic FIBA European Champions Cup [[three-peat]] (which the club, led by Kuko\u010d, achieved the following year), but he would not go to Boston either.\n\n===Rome===\nIn August 1990, instead of going to the [[NBA]] as previously agreed, Ra\u0111a went to Italy, signing with the wealthy [[Pallacanestro Virtus Roma|Virtus Roma]] despite claiming all along that he had wanted to join the Celtics.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1990-03-19/sports/sp-504_1_boston-celtics Radja Says Club Is Ready to Let Him Be a Celtic];''Los Angeles Times'', 19 March 1990</ref> He changed his mind once Virtus, an ambitious and financially stable club bankrolled by the [[:it:Ferruzzi|Gruppo Ferruzzi]] food company and sponsored by the daily broadsheet ''[[Il Messaggero]]'', made him an offer reportedly in the [[US$]]15\u201318 million range for a 5-year contract.<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite magazine | url = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1136568/index.htm | author = [[Jack McCallum]] | title = Close But No Cigar: The sagging Celts were spurned by Brian Shaw and by Dino Radja | magazine = [[Sports Illustrated]] | date = 13 August 1990 | accessdate = 23 February 2012}}</ref> Italian and Yugoslav newspapers reported that Ra\u0111a's annual salary at the time, [[Italian lira|L]]3.6 billion, at Virtus was higher than soccer superstars [[Diego Maradona]]'s and [[Roberto Baggio]]'s annual compensations at [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] and [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], respectively.<ref name=\"Zlatnimomci\">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yklhi8h1Cu4&t=1322|first1=Vladimir|last1=Paji\u0107|first2=Milo\u0161|last2=\u0160akan|title=Zlatni momci (episode 3): Tim snova u luna parku|agency=[[Radio Television of Serbia]]|date=28 August 2019|accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> The Boston Celtics did not insist on Ra\u0111a honouring his commitment to them, instead letting the twenty-three-year-old go to Virtus in return for an undisclosed amount,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1990/08/03/sports/sports-people-pro-basketball-radja-to-roma-team-for-two-seasons.html Radja to Roma Team For Two Seasons];''The New York Times'', 3 August 1990</ref> but retaining his NBA rights. Reportedly, part of the reason Boston did not put up much of a fight when the player suddenly decided to sign with Virtus was the July 1990 court decision against them following the motion by Ra\u0111a's American [[sports agent|agent]], Marc Fleisher, after the Virtus offer came in. Taking advantage of an administrative loophole,<ref>{{cite news|last=Arace|first=Michael|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-08-23/sports/sp-1950_1_reggie-lewis|title=Reggie Lewis Signed Up by Celtics for 5 Years|agency=''[[Los Angeles Times]]''|date=23 August 1990|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> Fleisher claimed that Ra\u0111a's contract with the Celtics violated a provision of the agreement between the league and the NBA players that said, among other things, that one-year contracts could not be extended. A special officer of the court had heard the case and ruled in Ra\u0111a's favour, against the Celtics.<ref name=\"SI\"/>\n\nSimultaneous to the legal battle his agent was waging over the future of his club career, Ra\u0111a had been spending the summer of 1990 with the [[Yugoslavia national basketball team|Yugoslav national team]] in a four-month training camp for the [[1990 FIBA World Championship]] that included an appearance at the [[1990 Goodwill Games]] in [[Seattle]] where the 23-year-old suffered a leg fracture in the final game against the [[United States men's national basketball team|U.S. national team]], ruling him out of the World Championship that started a week later. Yugoslavia head coach [[Du\u0161an Ivkovi\u0107]] later revealed that injured Ra\u0111a and the center's agent Marc Fleisher asked him not to publicly disclose the player's injury before the deal with Virtus is signed, which Ivkovi\u0107 consented to.<ref name=\"Zlatnimomci\"/>\n\nSome observers saw Virtus' sudden and lucrative contract offer to Ra\u0111a as their retribution to the Celtics for going to court a few months earlier over enforcing Virtus' point guard [[Brian Shaw]]'s NBA contract and winning the case even after the player who had spent the previous 1989-90 season with Virtus tried to remain in Rome.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com.au/boston/nba/columns/story?columnist=may_peter&id=5685362|first=Peter|last=May|title=Erden brings new dimension to C's|newspaper=[[ESPN.com]]|date=14 October 2010|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, commenting on his summer 1990 decision to stay in Europe, even after only a year prior seeming desperately intent on playing in the NBA, Ra\u0111a said: {{cquote|''I was playing well. I was making a great salary in Europe. The thing about playing in the NBA was that there were so many unknowns. The NBA was more physical because the players were bigger and stronger than in Europe. I also would have had to get used to an entirely different culture''.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=eMPHqkXjbM0C&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=Radja+Vrankovic+Boston+Celtics&source=bl&ots=_L--OZung3&sig=6zebbkVqSW2dk4GHtGaH-6grLUM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FcVNUZ2SEoLi4AO67oHoDA&ved=0CCwQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=Radja%20Vrankovic%20Boston%20Celtics&f=false Boston Celtics: Where Have You Gone?];Mike Carey, Michael D. McClellan 2005, p.52</ref>}}\n\n====1990-91 season====\nRa\u0111a averaged 17.9 points in the [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italian League]]<ref name=\"web.legabasket.it\">[http://web.legabasket.it/player/?id=RAD-DIN-67 Dino Radja MEDIE STAGIONE {{in lang|it}}.]</ref> in his first season with [[Pallacanestro Virtus Roma|Il Messaggero]] (Virtus Roma enjoyed sponsorship from that [[Il Messaggero|popular Roman newspaper]] at the time). European sports journalists voted him the second best European player that season, behind only his former teammate and friend Kuko\u010d.\n\nHe improved his scoring average each of the next two seasons with the Roman club, averaging 20.3 and 21.7 points in the Italian League,<ref name=\"web.legabasket.it\"/> respectively.\n\nIn 1992, he [[1991\u201392 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup|led]] Virtus to a [[European professional club basketball system|European 3rd-tier level]] [[FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup]] title.\n\n===Boston Celtics===\nRa\u0111a finally joined the Celtics in the summer of 1993, signing a three-year contract on 9 July,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1993/07/10/sports/sports-people-basketball-celtics-complete-radja-deal.html Celtics Complete Radja Deal];''The New York Times'', 10 July 1993</ref> four years after initial interest from both parties and the voided contract in 1989. Some two and a half weeks later, the team went through a shocking incident when the Celtics' leading scorer, [[small forward]] [[Reggie Lewis]], died on the basketball court at the team's [[Brandeis University]] practice facility after suffering [[sudden cardiac death]] from a heart defect.\n\nPlaying alongside [[Dee Brown (basketball, born 1968)|Dee Brown]], 40-year-old veteran [[Robert Parish]], and [[Rick Fox]], twenty-six-year-old Ra\u0111a averaged 15.1 points and 7.2 rebounds in his [[1993\u201394 Boston Celtics season|debut season]] during which he made $1.5 million in salary.<ref>[http://articles.courant.com/1993-11-02/sports/0000002573_1_dino-radja-celtics-coach-chris-ford-dave-gavitt Celtics' Radja Proving He Belongs];''Hartford Courant'', 2 November 1993</ref> With a 32\u201350 regular season record, the Celtics missed the NBA playoffs, finishing 10th overall in the eastern conference. At the end of the season, Ra\u0111a was voted to the [[NBA All-Rookie Team|NBA All-Rookie Second Team]], along with Kuko\u010d, who had just completed his rookie campaign with the [[Chicago Bulls]].\n\nIn early November 1994, at the start of [[1994\u201395 Boston Celtics season|his second season]] with the Celtics, Ra\u0111a was looking for a contract extension on his existing three-year deal, which was expiring in the summer of 1996. With his agent Mark Fleisher engaged in long negotiations<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924201131/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8303175.html Radja looks like lost cause With extension unlikely, escape looms];''The Boston Globe'', 8 November 1994</ref> with the Celtics brass led by GM Jan Volk, the deal was reached to add three more years to Ra\u0111a's existing contract beginning with the 1996\u201397 season.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1290&dat=19941109&id=B1JUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=t40DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3311,4386566 Celtics, Radja agree contract extension];''Boca Raton News'', 9 November 1994</ref>\n\nThe 1996\u201397 season, Ra\u0111a's fourth in Boston, was marked by a left knee injury that forced him to miss 57 regular season games. In January 1997, he underwent [[arthroscopic surgery]] on his knee. The Celtics finished the season dead-last in their division, with a 15\u201367 record, the worst in the eastern conference, forcing a coaching change at the end of the season, with [[Rick Pitino]] replacing [[M. L. Carr]].\n\nIn June 1997, a trade that was to send thirty-year-old Ra\u0111a to the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] (in exchange for [[Clarence Weatherspoon]] and [[Michael Cage]]) fell through when Ra\u0111a failed his 24 June 1997 physical with the 76ers. Apparently, the 76ers staffers that examined Ra\u0111a determined he had no [[cartilage]] in his left knee, estimating that \"because his left knee is bone-on-bone, he can play games, but he can't practice afterwards, because his knee will swell\" and that \"he can't play four games in six days\".<ref>[http://articles.philly.com/1997-06-27/sports/25525198_1_sixers-dino-radja-nets-trade Boston Drops Radja Challenge];''The Inquirer'', 27 June 1997</ref> The Celtics initially challenged the 76ers' decision to void the trade, but quickly dropped their arbitration request. Ra\u0111a had three more years left on his guaranteed contract and, according to the NBA regulations, if he was to fail another team's physical, the Celtics would have to pay his entire remaining salary. Unconvinced about Ra\u0111a's physical condition, the Celtics gave up on trying to trade him, instead agreeing a buyout of the three years that remained on his contract. Following the buyout, the Celtics waived Ra\u0111a on 16 July 1997.\n\nIn 2005, Ra\u0111a talked about his exit from Boston: {{cquote|''I went to Pitino and asked him if I fit into his plans. With a new coach, I obviously wanted to know what he thought of my game. I loved playing for Boston and just wanted to find out if there was any possibility I might be traded, because I had heard some rumours. Pitino looked me right in the eyes and said, \"Dino, don't worry. You're going to be a big part of our offense. When we run a set play, the ball is going to go through you.' I left the meeting feeling great. Five days later, I found out I was being traded to Philadelphia. I can't tell you how much I felt betrayed. Either Pitino lied or something changed in a matter of a few days.\"<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=eMPHqkXjbM0C&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=Radja+Vrankovic+Boston+Celtics&source=bl&ots=_L--OZung3&sig=6zebbkVqSW2dk4GHtGaH-6grLUM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FcVNUZ2SEoLi4AO67oHoDA&ved=0CCwQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=Radja%20Vrankovic%20Boston%20Celtics&f=false Boston Celtics: Where Have You Gone?];Mike Carey, Michael D. McClellan 2005, p.54</ref>}}\n\nOver the course of his four seasons with the Celtics, Ra\u0111a averaged 16.7 points and 8.4 rebounds per game in the regular season. In the NBA playoffs, where he only made a single appearance with four games played, he averaged 15.0 points and 7.0 rebounds per game.\n\n===Return to Europe: Panathinaikos===\nIn the wake of his failed physical in Philadelphia and Rick Pitino's unwillingness to keep him on the Celtics' roster, Ra\u0111a returned to Europe in July 1997, joining [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]], a rich and ambitious club bankrolled by the Giannakopoulos brothers ([[Pavlos Giannakopoulos|Pavlos]] and [[Thanasis Giannakopoulos|Thanasis]]) who made their money in the pharmaceutical industry.\n\nFor Panathinaikos' owners, finishing the previous 1996\u201397 season without any trophies (having previously, in the 1995\u201396 season, won both the [[FIBA European League]] and the [[Greek Basketball Cup|Greek Cup]]) was deemed unacceptable, bringing about big changes to the team. The team's head coach [[Bo\u017eidar Maljkovi\u0107]] (Ra\u0111a's mentor from his Split days) had already been released during the previous failed season, while his interim replacement, Michalis Kokalis, was let go in the summer of 1997 to make way for new head coach [[Slobodan Suboti\u0107]]. Also coming in alongside Ra\u0111a and coach Suboti\u0107, was 36-year-old NBA veteran [[Byron Scott (basketball)|Byron Scott]] from the [[LA Lakers]].\n\nRa\u0111a spent two years in Athens, winning two [[Greek Basket League|Greek League]] championships, but in 1999, he returned to his native Croatia, to play for [[KK Zadar|Zadar]]. He left Panathinaikos partly because of an encounter with [[Pavlos Giannakopoulos|the club president]]'s son, [[Dimitrios Giannakopoulos]], in the locker room after a game. The president's son, [[Dimitrios Giannakopoulos|Dimitrios]], allegedly cursed at the team's head coach Suboti\u0107, but at that time, Ra\u0111a did not know that the person he was arguing with was the son of the club's president.<ref>http://www.blog.hr/print/id/1623177546/dezbjego-show-slobodan-subotic.html {{in lang|hr}}</ref> He left the club at the end of the season, after winning the Greek League finals against [[Olympiacos B.C.|Olympiacos]].\n\nIn 2000, he returned to Greece, joining Panathinaikos' long-time rivals, [[Olympiacos B.C.|Olympiacos]], in an unsuccessful attempt to regain the Greek League championship. With Olympiacos, on 16 October 2000, he scored his first points in the [[EuroLeague]] competition, under its new format in which it was run by [[Euroleague Basketball]], in a match against [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]].<ref>http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/5teeg5mf8yhh44wj/euroleague-s-500-000th-point-scored-on-friday</ref>\n\nHe returned, once again, to Croatia, joining [[KK Cibona|Cibona]] for the 2001\u201302 season. Ra\u0111a finished his career in 2003, by winning the [[A1 Liga|Croatian League]] championship with his first team, [[KK Split|Split CO]].\n\n==National team career==\nRa\u0111a was on the senior men's [[Yugoslavian national basketball team|Yugoslavian national team]] that won the silver medal in the [[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1988 Summer Olympic Games]] in [[Seoul]]. He was also a part of the golden Yugoslavian teams at the [[1987 FIBA Under-19 World Championship]] in [[Bormio]], Italy, [[EuroBasket 1989]] in [[Zagreb]] and the [[EuroBasket 1991]] in Rome.\n\nFollowing Croatia's independence, Ra\u0111a became an important player of the senior men's [[Croatian national basketball team]], most notably at the [[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1992 Summer Olympic Games]] in [[Barcelona]], where Croatia won the silver medal. Ra\u0111a was also on the Croatian teams that won the bronze at the [[EuroBasket 1993]] in Germany, [[1994 FIBA World Championship]] in [[Toronto]], and the [[EuroBasket 1995]] in [[Athens]]. With 1,764 points scored, he was the all-time top scorer for the Croatian national team until 2018, when he was surpassed by [[Bojan Bogdanovi\u0107]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/kapetan-zabio-1471-kos-ukic-postao-treci-najbolji-strijelac-hrvatske-svih-vremena--znate-li-tko-su-prva-dvojica-/1217742/|title=Uki\u0107 tre\u0107i najbolji strijelac Hrvatske svih vremena, znate li tko su prva dvojica?|work=[[Jutarnji list]]|date=4 September 2014|language=Croatian|accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.index.hr/sport/clanak/bogdanovic-novi-hrvatski-rekorder-u-poenima-prestigao-radju/2023912.aspx|title=Bogdanovi\u0107 novi hrvatski rekorder u poenima: Prestigao Ra\u0111u|date=14 September 2018|work=[[Index.hr]]|language=hr|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==NBA career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===Regular season===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1993}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1993\u201394 Boston Celtics season|Boston]]\n| '''80''' || 47 || 28.8 || '''.521''' || .000 || .751 || 7.2 || 1.4 || .9 || .8 || 15.1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1994}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1994\u201395 Boston Celtics season|Boston]]\n| 66 || 48 || 32.5 || .490 || .000 || '''.759''' || 8.7 || 1.7 || .9 || 1.3 || 17.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1995}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1995\u201396 Boston Celtics season|Boston]]\n| 53 || '''52''' || '''37.4''' || .500 || {{sort|-|\u2014}} || .695 || '''9.8''' || 1.6 || .9 || 1.5 || '''19.7'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1996}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1996\u201397 Boston Celtics season|Boston]]\n| 25 || 25 || 35.0 || .440 || .000 || .718 || 8.4 || '''1.9''' || .9 || '''1.9''' || 14.0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Career\n| 224 || 172 || 32.6 || .497 || .000 || .735 || 8.4 || 1.6 || .9 || 1.3 || 16.7\n{{s-end}}\n\n===Playoffs===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1995 NBA Playoffs|1995]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1994\u201395 Boston Celtics season|Boston]]\n| 4 || 3 || 38.3 || .400 || {{sort|-|\u2014}} || .714 || 7.0 || 2.3 || 1.0 || 1.3 || 15.0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Career\n| 4 || 3 || 38.3 || .400 || {{sort|-|\u2014}} || .714 || 7.0 || 2.3 || 1.0 || 1.3 || 15.0\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Career achievements==\n\n===Club titles===\n* 2\u00d7 [[FIBA European Champions Cup]] winner: [[1988\u201389 FIBA European Champions Cup|1988\u201389]], [[1989\u201390 FIBA European Champions Cup|1989\u201390]]\n* [[FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup]] winner: 1991\u201392\n* 3\u00d7 [[Yugoslav First Basketball League|Yugoslav League]] champion: 1987\u201388, 1988\u201389, 1989\u201390\n* [[Yugoslav Basketball Cup|Yugoslav Cup]] winner: 1989\u201390\n* 2\u00d7 [[Greek Basket League|Greek League]] champion: 1997\u201398, 1998\u201399\n* 2\u00d7 [[A-1 Liga|Croatian League]] champion: 2001\u201302, 2002\u201303\n* 2\u00d7 [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107 Cup|Croatian Cup]] winner: 1999\u20132000, 2001\u201302\n\n===Awards===\n* [[EuroLeague Final Four MVP|FIBA European Champions Cup Final Four MVP]]: 1989\n* [[Lega Basket All Star Game|Italian All-Star Game]] MVP: 1991\n* [[FIBA European Selection]]: 1991\n* [[FIBA's 50 Greatest Players]]: 1991\n* [[NBA All-Rookie Second Team]]: {{nbay|1993|end}}\n* 3\u00d7 [[FIBA EuroStar]]: 1997, 1998, 1999\n* [[Greek Basket League Finals MVP|Greek League Finals MVP]]: 1998\n* [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107 Cup|Croatian Cup Final Four MVP]]: 2000\n* Croatian Cup Final Four Top Scorer: 2000\n* [[50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors]]: 2008\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{basketballstats|nba=129|bbr=r/radjadi01}}\n* [http://www.euroleague.net/competition/players/showplayer?pcode=AHA#!careerstats Dino Ra\u0111a] at euroleague.net\n* [http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/lid_38135_cp/1/pid/2648/q/dino%20radja/rpp//_//players.html Dino Ra\u0111a] at fiba.com (archive)\n* [http://www.fibaeurope.com/compID_GSf9wrCdHBkDZZk9UQoqE3.season_2000.roundID_2532.playerID_2648.teamID_1169.html Dino Ra\u0111a] at fibaeurope.com\n* [http://web.legabasket.it/player/?id=RAD-DIN-67 Dino Ra\u0111a] legabasket.it {{in lang|it}}\n\n{{navboxes|list=\n{{FIBA50}}\n{{Euroleague50}}\n{{Euroleague Final Four MVP Award}}\n{{Greek Basket League Finals MVPs}}\n{{Olympiacos B.C.}}\n{{Panathinaikos B.C.}}\n{{KK Split 1988\u201389 Euroleague champions}}\n{{1989 NBA Draft}}\n{{KK Split 1989\u201390 Euroleague champions}}\n{{Pallacanestro Virtus Roma 1991\u201392 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup champions}}\n{{Yugoslavia Squad EuroBasket 1987}}\n{{Footer 1988 Olympic Silver Medalists Basketball Men}}\n{{Yugoslavia Squad EuroBasket 1989}}\n{{Yugoslavia Squad EuroBasket 1991}}\n{{Footer 1992 Olympic Silver Medalists Basketball Men}}\n{{Croatia Squad EuroBasket 1993}}\n{{Croatia Squad 1994 FIBA World Championship}}\n{{Croatia Squad EuroBasket 1995}}\n{{Croatia Men Basketball Squad 1996 Summer Olympics}}\n{{2018 Basketball HOF}}\n{{Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rada, Dino}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:ABA League players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1992 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Boston Celtics draft picks]]\n[[Category:Boston Celtics players]]\n[[Category:Centers (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriate basketball people in Greece]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriate basketball people in Italy]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Croatian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:FIBA EuroBasket-winning players]]\n[[Category:Greek Basket League players]]\n[[Category:KK Cibona players]]\n[[Category:KK Split players]]\n[[Category:KK Zadar players]]\n[[Category:Lega Basket Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1992 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association players from Croatia]]\n[[Category:Olympiacos B.C. players]]\n[[Category:Olympic basketball players of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Olympic basketball players of Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in basketball]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Croatia]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:Pallacanestro Virtus Roma players]]\n[[Category:Panathinaikos B.C. players]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Split, Croatia]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav men's basketball players]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "add category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dino_Ra%C4%91a"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Gaze", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Andrew Gaze\n| image = Andrew gaze.JPG\n| caption = Gaze at a [[Melbourne Tigers]] home game in 2011\n| height_cm = 201\n| weight_kg = 95\n| position = \n| league = \n| team =\n| nationality = Australian\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1965|7|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| high_school = [[Albert Park College]]<br>(Melbourne, Victoria)\n| college = [[Seton Hall Pirates men's basketball|Seton Hall]] (1988\u20131989)\n| draft_year = 1989\n| career_number = 10\n| career_position = [[Shooting guard]]<!-- Please do NOT add point guard without providing a reliable source to back that up. He's noted as a shooting guard here https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/g/gazean01.html and here https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2014/may/13/the-joy-of-six-australians-in-the-nba -->\n| career_start = 1984\n| career_end = 2005\n| coach_start = 2016\n| coach_end = \n| years1 = 1984\u20132005\n| team1 = [[Melbourne Tigers]]\n| years2 = 1991\u20131992\n| team2 = [[Pallalcesto Amatori Udine|Udine]]\n| years3 = {{nbay|1993|end}}\n| team3 = [[Washington Bullets]]\n| years4 = 1995\n| team4 = [[Apollon Patras B.C.|Apollon Patras]]\n| years5 = {{nbay|1998|end}}\n| team5 = [[San Antonio Spurs]]\n| cyears1 = 2016\u20132017\n| cteam1 = [[Melbourne Basketball Association|Melbourne Tigers]] (SEABL)\n| cyears2 = 2016\u20132019\n| cteam2 = [[Sydney Kings]]\n| stats_league = NBL\n| stat1label = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value = 18,908 (30.8 ppg)\n| stat2label = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value = 3,121 (5.1 rpg)\n| stat3label = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value = 3,531 (5.8 apg)\n| highlights = \n*[[List of NBA champions|NBA champion]] ([[1999 NBA Finals|1999]])\n*2\u00d7 [[List of NBL champions|NBL champion]] (1993, 1997)\n*7\u00d7 [[NBL Most Valuable Player Award|NBL MVP]] (1991, 1992, 1994\u20131998)\n*11\u00d7 [[NBL (Australia) All-Star Game|NBL All-Star]] (1988\u20131997, 2004)\n*2\u00d7 NBL All-Star Game MVP (1989, 1992)\n*15\u00d7 [[All-NBL Team|All-NBL First Team]] (1986\u20132000)\n* [[All-NBL Team|All-NBL Second Team]] (2001)\n*8\u00d7 [[NBL Most Efficient Player Award|NBL Most Efficient Player]] (1990\u20131997)\n*[[NBL Rookie of the Year Award|NBL Rookie of the Year]] (1984)\n*14\u00d7 [[List of National Basketball League (Australia) annual scoring leaders|NBL scoring champion]] (1986, 1988, 1989, 1991\u20132001)<!-- Gaze was not the scoring champion in 1987 & 1990 https://web.archive.org/web/20170923062541/http://nbl.gearbox.performgroup.com/nbl-all-time-leaders -->\n*NBL assist champion (1989)\n* [[NBL (Australia) 20th Anniversary Team|NBL 20th Anniversary Team]] (1998)\n* [[NBL (Australia) 25th Anniversary Team|NBL 25th Anniversary Team]] (2003)\n* NBL 40th Anniversary Team (2018)\n* No. 10 [[Melbourne United#Retired jerseys|retired by Melbourne Tigers]]\n*6\u00d7 [[Australian International Player of the Year|Gaze Medalist]] (1990, 1994\u20131996, 1998, 2000)\n*[[FIBA's 50 Greatest Players]] (1991)\n*[[Australian Basketball Hall of Fame]] (2004)\n*[[Sport Australia Hall of Fame]] (2005)\n| FIBA_HOF_player = Andrew-Gaze\n}}\n'''Andrew Barry Casson Gaze''', [[Order of Australia|AM]] (born 24 July 1965) is an Australian former professional [[basketball]] player and coach. He played 22 seasons in the [[National Basketball League (Australia)|National Basketball League]] (NBL) with the [[Melbourne Tigers]] from 1984 to 2005, winning the league's [[NBL Most Valuable Player Award|MVP award]] seven times and winning the [[List of National Basketball League (Australia) annual scoring leaders|scoring title]] 14 times. He also guided the Tigers to two NBL championships, in 1993 and 1997, and was named an [[All-NBL Team|All-NBL First Team]] member for a record high 15 consecutive years. Gaze has been described as one of the greatest players Australia has ever produced.<ref>{{cite web|last=Scanlan|first=Alex|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/media-academy/he-set-records-galore-in-the-nbl-but-has-andrew-gaze-been-usurped-as-our-best-ever-basketballer/news-story/ed5059560e0e9e7ed9fd354eb1bd2979|title=He set records galore in the NBL but has Andrew Gaze been usurped as our best ever basketballer?|work=FoxSports.com|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbl.com.au/featured-news/q-a-with-andrew-gaze/|title=Q & A WITH ANDREW GAZE|work=NBL.com.au|date=7 April 2016|accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nGaze led the senior [[Australia men's national basketball team|Australian national team]], the Boomers, to five [[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympic Games]] \u2013 including as the [[List of flag bearers for Australia at the Olympics|flag bearer]] at the [[2000 Summer Olympics opening ceremony|opening ceremony]] of the [[2000 Sydney Olympics]], and he was also the Australian [[captain (sports)|Team Captain]]. He was inducted into the [[Australian Basketball Hall of Fame]] in 2004, and the [[Sport Australia Hall of Fame]] in 2005, after becoming a member of the [[Order of Australia]] in 2002. In 2013, he joined his father, [[Lindsay Gaze|Lindsay]], in the [[FIBA Hall of Fame]], to become just the third Australian inductee.<ref name=fame>[http://www.basketball.net.au/andrew-gaze-inducted-into-fiba-hall-of-fame/ ANDREW GAZE INDUCTED INTO FIBA HALL OF FAME]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140112135103/http://www.tigers.com.au/article/id/182havmjo4ndg17i5if77snwuf Basketball legend ANDREW GAZE inducted into FIBA Hall Of Fame]</ref> Two Australian basketball awards have been named in Gaze's honour: the NBL MVP award is named the Andrew Gaze Trophy, and the [[Australian International Player of the Year]] award is named the Gaze Medal.\n\n==Early life and family==\nGaze was born in [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], the son of Lindsay and Margaret Gaze, and has an older sister, Janet. Gaze is also the nephew of former [[Australian Opals]] coach Tony Gaze and the cousin of Mark Gaze, who played 182 games in the NBL from 1983\u20131991 and represented Australia at the [[1982 FIBA World Championship]]. He is also the second cousin of [[Canberra Capitals]] guard [[Kate Gaze]], the daughter of Mark Gaze and former WNBL player Michelle O'Connor.\n\nGaze grew up at [[Albert Park Basketball Stadium]], the home of the Victorian Basketball Association (VBA), with his father the general manager of the VBA at the time. After graduating from [[Albert Park College]], Gaze pursued a professional basketball career and attended [[Victoria University, Australia|Victoria University]] in Melbourne.\n\n==Playing career==\n===NBL and college===\nIn 1984, Gaze joined the [[Melbourne Tigers]] of the [[National Basketball League (Australia)|National Basketball League]] as an 18-year-old. His first season with the Tigers saw him win the [[NBL Rookie of the Year Award]] after averaging an impressive 29.1 points, 6.7 rebounds, 4.1 assists and 1.6 steals in 24 games.<ref name=\"nbl-stats\">[http://www.foxsportspulse.com/team_info.cgi?action=PSTATS&pID=190395826&client=0-189-12322-125703-369917 Player statistics for Andrew Gaze]</ref> By 1986, he made his first [[All-NBL Team|All-NBL First Team]] selection. He would go on to earn first-team honours in 15 straight seasons (1986\u20132000). In the [[1987 NBL season]], Gaze set an NBL record for points per game in a season when he averaged 44.1 points. This was despite the Tigers finishing the season in last place with a 3\u201323 record. During the season, Gaze had a 60-point game (against the [[Newcastle Falcons (basketball)|Newcastle Falcons]]) and another five 50-point games.\n\nFollowing the [[1988 NBL season]], Gaze, who was spotted by talent scouts while playing for Australia at the [[1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Olympics]], moved to the United States after being recruited to play [[college basketball]] for [[Seton Hall Pirates men's basketball|Seton Hall University]]. During the 1988\u201389 season, Gaze played in 38 games for the Seton Hall Pirates, averaging 13.6 points, 4.5 rebounds and 2.9 assists per game.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/andrew-gaze-1.html Andrew Gaze College Stats]</ref> Gaze started every game in The Hall's [[1989 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|first-ever run to the NCAA Final Four]], twice leading all Pirates scorers with 19 points in their Elite Eight win over [[UNLV Runnin' Rebels men's basketball|UNLV]] and 20 points (highlighted by 4-from-9 shooting from 3) in the National Semifinal win against [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]]. He completed his season at Seton Hall with an 80\u201379 overtime loss to the [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan Wolverines]] in the NCAA Championship Game which was played in front of 39,187 fans at the [[Kingdome]] in [[Seattle]], where he was heavily guarded and limited to only five field goal attempts, all from three-point range. After a year in New Jersey, Gaze returned to Australia and re-joined the Tigers for the [[1989 NBL season]].<ref name=\"Gaze Is Gone But Questions Arise\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1989/04/14/sports/gaze-is-gone-but-questions-arise.html Gaze Is Gone But Questions Arise]</ref> He missed the back-end of the [[1990 NBL season]] due to a blood clot in his right shoulder.<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1990-09-11-sp-434-story.html THE SIDELINES : Clot Hospitalizes Andrew Gaze]</ref>\n\nNot known for being an outstanding athlete, Gaze's heavy scoring in the NBL was due to exceptional shooting, including from three-point range. A crowd favourite to the Tigers faithful, Gaze was a front runner in the league's resurgence during the 1990s, as he and American import [[Lanard Copeland]] combined to form a formidable backcourt and guided the Tigers to two championships in 1993 and 1997.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AJ9Yd5upYr0 Andrew Gaze and Lanard Copeland]</ref> Playing under his father with the Tigers, Gaze assured the team were perpetual finalists.\n\nIn his later years, Gaze still managed to score at a high clip for the Tigers, averaging over 19 points per game in each of his last four NBL seasons. Following the [[2004\u201305 NBL season]], Gaze announced his retirement from the NBL. In 20 seasons with the Tigers, he played a total of 612 games and recorded 18,908 points at an average of 30.9 points per game.<ref name=\"nbl-stats\" />\n\n===Europe and NBA===\nIn addition to playing in the NBL, Gaze spent multiple seasons overseas during the 1990s. In 1991, Gaze became the first Australian to play professionally in Europe, with [[Serie A2 Basket|Italian 2nd League]] club [[Pallalcesto Amatori Udine|Udine]]. In a six-month stint in Italy, he averaged over 30 points per game.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100818154617/http://www.musictheatreaustralia.com.au/component/entertainers/andrew_gaze/4779 Andrew Gaze \u2013 Music Theatre Australia]</ref>Despite his best efforts, the team finished the league last and was relegated to the [[Serie B Basket|3rd division]]. In March 1994, Gaze returned to the United States and signed with the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]'s [[Washington Bullets]]. In seven games for the Bullets during the [[1993\u201394 NBA season]], he averaged 3.1 points per game. In early 1995, he moved to Greece and played half a season for [[Greek Basket League|Greek League]] club [[Apollon Patras B.C.|Apollon Patras]].<ref>[https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/rec.sport.basketball.misc/-9Y_MX8v7ts Andrew Gaze playing in Greece]</ref> He had another short stint in the NBA during the lockout-shortened [[1998\u201399 NBA season|1998\u201399 season]], this time with the [[San Antonio Spurs]]. He received very little court time for a stacked [[1998\u201399 San Antonio Spurs season|Spurs team]] that included guards [[Mario Elie]], [[Avery Johnson]], [[Antonio Daniels]] and [[Steve Kerr]]. He appeared in just 19 games for the Spurs during the regular season and was inactive for the entire [[1999 NBA Playoffs|playoff run]], which saw the Spurs win their first [[1999 NBA Finals|NBA championship]].<ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/g/gazean01.html Andrew Gaze NBA Stats]</ref>\n\n===National team===\nOn the international stage, Gaze forged his reputation as one of Australia's finest products, appearing at the [[Basketball at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Los Angeles Olympic Games]], as a 19-year-old. He led all scorers at the [[1994 FIBA World Championship]] with 23.9 points per game, leading the Aussies to a fifth-place finish. In [[Basketball at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2000]], he became (jointly with American [[Teresa Edwards]]) the third basketball player to compete at [[List of athletes with the most appearances at Olympic Games|five Olympics]], after Puerto Rican [[Te\u00f3filo Cruz]] and Brazilian [[Oscar Schmidt]]. That year, Gaze was the [[List of flag bearers for Australia at the Olympics|flag bearer]] at the [[2000 Summer Olympics opening ceremony|opening ceremony]] of the [[2000 Sydney Olympics|Sydney Olympics]], and he was also the Australian [[captain (sports)|Team Captain]]. At the [[1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Atlanta Olympics]], he led the [[Australia men's national basketball team|Boomers]] to their best Olympic performance, a fourth-placed finish, with a 5\u20133 record.<ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/olympics/athletes/andrew-gaze-1 Andrew Gaze Olympic Stats]</ref>\n\nGaze also competed in four [[FIBA World Cup]]s with the Boomers, as he played in more than 280 [[cap (sports)|matches]] for Australia. Gaze is the second best all-time scorer in both major worldwide [[national team]] competitions, after Oscar Schmidt. He is the second all-time scorer, behind only Schmidt, in both [[Basketball at the Summer Olympics#Top 10 all-time cumulative scorers in men's basketball (through 2016 Olympics)|Summer Olympic Games history]], and [[FIBA Basketball World Cup records#Top 10 cumulative points scorers|FIBA World Cup history]].<ref>[http://corporate.olympics.com.au/athlete/andrew-gaze Australian Olympic Committee: Andrew Gaze]</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nOn 8 December 2015, Gaze was appointed head coach of the [[Melbourne Basketball Association|Melbourne Tigers]] [[South East Australian Basketball League|SEABL]] team for the 2016 season.<ref>[http://www.seabl.com.au/index.php?id=257&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=10449&cHash=e4ca4e0edb ANDREW GAZE ANNOUNCED AS MELBOURNE TIGERS HEAD COACH]</ref><ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/sport/basketball/andrew-gaze-to-coach-melbourne-tigers-in-seabl-but-nbl-dreams-remain-20151208-gliii5.html Andrew Gaze to coach Melbourne Tigers in SEABL but NBL dreams remain]</ref> Gaze's cousin, Mark,<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/sport/basketball/australian-basketballers-making-big-impression-in-us-college-system-20131116-2xnnn.html Australian basketballers making big impression in US college system]</ref> was appointed the Tigers' assistant coach.\n\nOn 2 April 2016, Gaze was appointed head coach of the [[Sydney Kings]] on a three-year deal, joining a revitalised franchise with a new general manager, a new owner and new home venue.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160414100325/http://www.sydneykings.com/uncategorised/sydney-kings-announce-andrew-gaze-as-new-head-coach/ SYDNEY KINGS ANNOUNCE ANDREW GAZE AS NEW HEAD COACH]</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Gaze joined the [[Indiana Pacers]] as a member of their coaching staff for the [[2017 NBA Summer League|Orlando Summer League]].<ref>[http://www.nbl.com.au/featured-news/gaze-joins-indiana-pacers/ GAZE JOINS INDIANA PACERS]</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, the Kings confirmed Gaze as their head coach for the 2018\u201319 season.<ref>[https://www.foxsports.com.au/basketball/nbl/sydney-kings-confirm-andrew-gaze-as-head-coach-for-201819-nbl-season/news-story/d2a6e98e24700c65b2d646505c63cadc Sydney Kings confirm Andrew Gaze as head coach for 2018-19 NBL season]</ref> On 19 February 2019, it was announced that Gaze would step down as coach of the Kings at the conclusion of the team's finals campaign.<ref>[http://www.nbl.com.au/news/article/andrew-gaze-to-step-down-as-sydney-kings-coach-after-nbl19-finals Andrew Gaze To Step Down As Sydney Kings Coach After NBL19 Finals]</ref>\n\n==Off the court==\nAfter retiring from playing professionally, Gaze became a media personality and began commentating NBL games for [[Network Ten]] and [[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]]. He is also a presenter on [[Seven Network|Channel Seven]]'s ''[[Guide to the Good Life]]'' and on ''[[Bounce (Australian TV series)|Bounce]]'' on Fox Footy. In 2006, he appeared in season five of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (Australian TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/news/tv--radio/gaze-bounces-out-of-show/2006/11/15/1163266590272.html Gaze bounces out of show]</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Gaze became an ambassador for the non-for-profit organisation ''The Beehive Foundation'', a charity that runs free programs to develop resilience and coping mechanisms for youth via junior sporting organisations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.beehivefoundation.org.au/#!ambassadors/clgp |title=Ambassadors |work=BeehiveFoundation.org.au |accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/BeehiveFoundation/photos/a.257382911041721.57487.249530845160261/945321078914564/ |title=We are extremely excited to announce that Basketball Legend and media... |work=Facebook.com |date=22 March 2016 |accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nGaze and his wife Melinda have four children; Courtney, Phoebe, Annie and Mason. In 2014, he was named Australian Father of the Year by children's charity ''The Shepherd Centre''.<ref>[http://www.basketball.net.au/australian-basketball-legend-andrew-gaze-named-2014-australian-father-year/ Basketball legend Andrew Gaze named 2014 Australian Father of the Year]</ref>\n\n==Records, honours and awards==\n*Record for most [[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympic Games]] for an Australian basketball player (5 \u2013 [[Basketball at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984]], [[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988]], [[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics|1992]], [[Basketball at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996]] and [[Basketball at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2000]])\n*[[List of flag bearers for Australia at the Olympics|Flag bearer]] at the [[2000 Summer Olympics opening ceremony|opening ceremony]] of the [[2000 Sydney Olympics]] and the Australian [[captain (sports)|Team Captain]]\n*Inducted into the [[Australian Basketball Hall of Fame]] (2004), [[Sport Australia Hall of Fame]] (2005), and [[FIBA Hall of Fame]] (2013)\n*Was made a Member of the [[Order of Australia]] in 2002<ref name=\"fame\" />\n*[[National Basketball League (Australia)|NBL]] all-time:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aussiehoopla.com/nblrank-the-greatest-players-of-all-time-shooting-guard/|title=#NBLRANK THE GREATEST PLAYERS OF ALL TIME \u2013 SHOOTING GUARD|work=aussiehoopla.com|date=15 September 2016|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aussiehoopla.com/nbl-all-time-statistics/|title=NBL ALL-TIME STATISTICS|work=aussiehoopla.com|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref>\n**1st in Points \u2013 18,908\n**1st in Assists \u2013 3,531\n**1st in Field Goals Made \u2013 6,484\n**1st in 3-Pointers Made \u2013 1,826\n**1st in Free Throws Made \u2013 4,114\n**2nd in Games Played \u2013 612\n**3rd in Steals \u2013 1,075\n*NBL's highest single-season points per game average (44.1) (1987)\n*8\u00d7 NBL three-point field goal leader (1988, 1989, 1992, 1993, 1996\u20131999)\n*10\u00d7 NBL free-throw percentage leader (1990, 1992, 1994\u20131996, 1999, 2001\u20132004)\n*[[List of NBA champions|NBA champion]] ([[1999 NBA Finals|1999]])\n*2\u00d7 [[List of NBL champions|NBL champion]] (1993, 1997)\n*7\u00d7 [[NBL Most Valuable Player Award|NBL MVP]] (1991, 1992, 1994\u20131998)\n*15\u00d7 [[All-NBL Team|All-NBL First Team]] (1986\u20132000)\n*[[All-NBL Team|All-NBL Second Team]] (2001)\n*14\u00d7 [[List of National Basketball League (Australia) annual scoring leaders|NBL scoring champion]] (1986, 1988, 1989, 1991\u20132001)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbl.gearbox.performgroup.com/nbl-all-time-leaders|title=All Time Leaders|work=NBL.com.au|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923062541/http://nbl.gearbox.performgroup.com/nbl-all-time-leaders|archivedate=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n*NBL assist champion (1989)\n*11\u00d7 [[NBL (Australia) All-Star Game|NBL All-Star]] (1988\u20131997, 2004)\n*2\u00d7 NBL All-Star Game MVP (1989, 1992)\n*[[NBL Rookie of the Year Award|NBL Rookie of the Year]] (1984)\n*8\u00d7 [[NBL Most Efficient Player Award|NBL Most Efficient Player]] (1990\u20131997)\n*6\u00d7 [[Australian International Player of the Year|Gaze Medalist]] (1990, 1994\u20131996, 1998, 2000)\n*[[FIBA's 50 Greatest Players]] (1991)\n*[[Australian Basketball Hall of Fame]] (2004)\n*[[Sport Australia Hall of Fame]] (2005)\n*Was named a member of the NBL's 20th, 25th and 40th anniversary teams<ref>{{cite web|last=Ward|first=Roy|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/basketball/andrew-gaze-mark-bradtke-head-nbl-40th-anniversary-team-20180208-p4yzqg.html|title=Andrew Gaze, Mark Bradtke head NBL 40th anniversary team|work=Sydney Morning Herald|date=8 February 2018|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honour roll ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- align=left\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[National Basketball League (Australia)|NBL]] career: \n| 1984\u20132005\n|-align=left\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[List of NBL champions|NBL Championships]]: \n| 2\u00d7 (1993, 1997)\n|-\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[NBL Grand Final]] appearances: \n| 4\u00d7 (1992, 1993, 1996, 1997